0. Preparation

  • R and RStudio
    • R is a programming language and free software environment for statistical computing and graphics.
      You can download R from here for Windows users and here for Mac users.
    • RStudio is an integrated development environment (IDE) for R. (Wikipedia).
      To use RStudio, we need download R first. You can download Rstudio from here.
    • We can run R programs both in R and RStudio, but RSudio is recommended if you don’t have specific preferences.

  • Files in R
    • xxxx.Rproj : Rproject file
    • xxxx.Rmd : Rmarkdown file (this)
    • xxxx.R : script file (simplest to use)

  • Directory
    • Since we use Rstudio, we don’t have to set the working directory.
      Thus, we can skip the code of cd "Z: XXXXX" in Stat.

0.1. Library


Installing packages
We need to install packages first in R, using install.packages().
Once you install packages, we don’t have to run the following codes since the packages are saved in our local PC files.

install.packages("tidyverse")
install.packages("stargazer")
install.packages("foreign")
install.packages("readstata13")


Reading packages
We always need to read the required packages whenever we restart R program, using library().

library(tidyverse)    # data manipulation
library(stargazer)    # summarize data
library(foreign)      # read '.dta' file (Stata ver.15~)
library(readstata13)  # read '.dta' file (Stat old ver.)

0.2. Read data


Using foreign::read.dta(), we read the data file discrimination_data.dta in the folder 00_Input.

#--- read data ---#
df <- read.dta("./00_Input/lakisha_aer.dta")

1.2. Data manipulation

  • fnc : functions in both R and Stat
  • v1, v2, v3 : variables in the dataframe
  • x : specific condition


selection 

#--- Stata ver. ---#
fnc v1 v2 v3

#--- R ver. ---#
df %>% 
  dplyr::select(v1, v2, v3) %>%
  fnc()


conditioning 

#--- Stata ver. ---#
fnc if v1 == "x"

#--- R ver. ---#
df %>%
  filter(v1 == "x")
  fnc()


sorting 

#--- Stata ver. ---#
sort v1

#--- R ver. ---#
df %>% arrange(v1)


getting first x rows 

#--- Stata ver. ---#
list in 1/x

#--- R ver. ---#
df %>% head(n = x)


rename variable names 

#--- Stata ver. ---#
rename old_name new_name

#--- R ver. ---#
df %>% raname(old_name = new_name)

2. Table

2.1. Stat’s function table

Obviously, Stat is much easier than R.
* There might be an effective function for this in R, but I couldn’t find.

Create table according to race 

#--- Stata ver. ---#
** show the total number of candidates according to race
table race, contents(N education N yearsexp)

** show ave. and st.dev. according to race
table race, contents(mean education mean yearsexp sd education sd yearsexp)

** show calculate quantile according to race
table race, c(p25 yearsexp p50 yearsexp p75 yearsexp ) 



#--- R ver. ---#

## show the total number of candidates according to race
df %>%
  group_by(race) %>%
  summarise(N = n()) %>%
  as.data.frame()

## show ave. and st.dev. according to race
df %>% as.tibble() %>%
  group_by(race) %>%
  summarise_at(c("education", "yearsexp"), .funs = c(mean, sd), na.rm = TRUE) %>%
  as.data.frame()

## show calculate quantile according to race
df %>%
  group_by(race) %>%
  summarise_at("yearsexp", .funs = quantile, na.rm = TRUE) %>%
  mutate(position = c("min", "p25", "med", "p75", "max")) %>%
  pivot_wider(names_from = position, values_from = yearsexp) %>%
  as.data.frame()
##   race    N

2.2. Stat’s function tabulate

Obviously, Stat is much easier than R.
* There might be an effective function for this in R, but I couldn’t find.

Tabulate one variable

We need to create our own function in R to run the same function as tabulate in Stat.
* There might be an effective function for this in R, but I couldn’t find.

#--- Stata ver. ---#
tabulate yearsexp

#--- R ver. ---#

df %>% 
  #-- create group according to `yearsexp` --#
  group_by(yearsexp) %>%

  #-- count candidates according to `yearsexp` --#
  summarise(Freq. = n()) %>%
  as.data.frame() %>%

  #-- make `Percent` and `Cum.` --#
  mutate(
    # make a row of the total number of candidates
    Total = sum(Freq.),
    # calculate the ratio according to `yearsexp`; and manipulate the significant figures
    Percent = (Freq. / Total * 100) %>% sprintf("%1.3f", .) %>% as.numeric(),
    # calculate the cumulation; and manipulate the significant figures
    Cum. = cumsum(Percent) %>% sprintf("%1.2f", .) %>% as.numeric()
  ) %>% as.data.frame() %>%

  #-- drop the column `Total` --#
  dplyr::select(-Total)

2.3. R’s package stargazer

The package stargazer is a powerful tool to draw tables in R.
The usage of stargazer::stargazer() is similar to that of the function base::summary().
stargazer() has options for type, such as latex(default), html, text.
For more details, this is the best cheatsheet for stargazer by Jakerussr.

Get descriptive statistics 

#--- R ver. ---#

## LaTex
df %>%
  dplyr::filter(education == 4 & yearsexp > 20) %>%
  dplyr::select(education, yearsexp, sex) %>%
  stargazer(type = "latex")

## HTML for viewing in browser 
df %>%
  dplyr::filter(education == 4 & yearsexp > 20) %>%
  dplyr::select(education, yearsexp, sex) %>%
  stargazer(type = "html")

## text for viewing in RStudio or text file
df %>%
  dplyr::filter(education == 4 & yearsexp > 20) %>%
  dplyr::select(education, yearsexp, sex) %>%
  stargazer(type = "text")

2.4. Saving table

To save the tables generated by stargazer(), we use cat::capture.output(). 

#--- Stata ver. ---#

** install the package `outreg2`
ssc install outreg2

** save to MS Excel
outreg2 using race_1, replace sum(log) excel

** save to MS Word
outreg2 using race_1, replace sum(log) word
#--- R ver. ---#

## save to HTML
capture.output(
  df %>%
    dplyr::filter(education == 4 & yearsexp > 20) %>%
    dplyr::select(education, yearsexp, sex) %>%
    stargazer(type = "html"),
  file = "./00_Output/stat_dev.html",  ## designate the file name (html file)
  append = FALSE  ## `FALSE`: create a new file, `TRUE`: append to the existing file
)

## save to text
capture.output(
  df %>%
    dplyr::filter(education == 4 & yearsexp > 20) %>%
    dplyr::select(education, yearsexp, sex) %>%
    stargazer(type = "text"),
  file = "./00_Output/stat_dev.txt",  ## designate the file name (text file)
  append = FALSE  ## `FALSE`: create a new file, `TRUE`: append to the existing file
)


3. Figure

  • The package ggplot2 allows us to visualize beautiful figures in R though it is a little hard to master.
  • The package tidyverse which we have installed at first contains ggplot2;
    thus we don’t have to read the package like library(ggplot2).

3.1. Histgram

We use the functions of ggplot and geom_histgram in the package ggplot2, instead of hist in Stat.

Visualize histogram for two variables

We visualize histogram (density) of yearsexp according to race.

#--- Stata ver. ---#
hist yearsexp, by(race)

ggplot(data = df, aes(x = yearsexp, col = race, fill = race)) +  ## identify data and variables 
  geom_histogram(aes(y = ..density..), alpha = 0.5) +  ## identify density or frequency (default is freq.)
  facet_grid(.~ race) +  ## create grids
  theme_bw()  ## select theme

Combine multiple graphs

We use ggpubr::ggarrange() to combine multiple ggplot objects.
If you haven’t install the package ggpubr, run the following code install.packages("ggpubr")

#--- Stata ver. ---#
hist yearsexp if race == "b", name(b) 
hist yearsexp if race == "w", name(w)
graph combine b w

gg_black <- df %>%
  filter(race == "b") %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = yearsexp)) +  ## identify variables 
  geom_histogram(col = "red", fill = "red", alpha = 0.2) +  ## specify color
  theme_bw() +  ## select theme
  xlab("black")  ## change x-axis title

gg_white <- df %>%
  filter(race == "w") %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = yearsexp)) +  ## identify variables 
  geom_histogram(col = "blue", fill = "blue", alpha = 0.2) +  ## specify color
  theme_bw() +  ## select theme
  xlab("white")  ## change x-axis title

ggpubr::ggarrange(gg_black, gg_white)

Overlap multiple variables

We can choose several types of overlapping by specifying position =.
position has several parameters, such as identity(default), dodge, and stack.

#--- Stata ver. ---#
twoway (hist yearsexp if race == "b", freq disc color(green)) /*
　　　  　*/(hist yearsexp if race == "w", freq disc fcolor(none) lcolor(black)) /*
     */ ,legend(order(1 " Black" 2 "White" ))

## position = "identity"
gg_identity <- ggplot(data = df) +
  geom_histogram(position = "identity", aes(x = yearsexp, col = race, fill = race), alpha = 0.2) +
  theme_bw() + 
  ggtitle("identity")  ## insert a figure title

## position = "dodge"
gg_dodge <- ggplot(data = df) +
  geom_histogram(position = "dodge", aes(x = yearsexp, col = race, fill = race), alpha = 0.2) +
  theme_bw() +
  ggtitle("dodge")  ## insert a figure title

## position = "stack"
gg_stack <- ggplot(data = df) +
  geom_histogram(position = "stack", aes(x = yearsexp, col = race, fill = race), alpha = 0.2) +
  theme_bw() +
  ggtitle("stack")  ## insert a figure title

ggpubr::ggarrange(gg_identity, gg_dodge, gg_stack)

geom_density() draws a probability density function.

gg_identity_density <- ggplot(data = df) +
  geom_density(position = "identity", aes(x = yearsexp, col = race, fill = race), alpha = 0.2) +
  theme_bw() + 
  ggtitle("identity (geom_density)")  ## insert a figure title

gg_stack_density <- ggplot(data = df) +
  geom_density(position = "stack", aes(x = yearsexp, col = race, fill = race), alpha = 0.2) +
  theme_bw() +
  ggtitle("stack (geom_density)")  ## insert a figure title

ggpubr::ggarrange(gg_identity_density, gg_stack_density)

4. T-test

We use t.test() for the t-test in R, instead of ttest in Stat.

Before starting t-test, we need to convert string variables to numeric variables.

variable data type example conversion
yearsexp numeric 3, 7, 12 non-necessary
education numeric (category) 1–4 non-necessary
call numeric (dummy) 0 or 1 non-necessary
race string “b” or “w” necessary

In this case, we convert each element of race as follows: "b" to 1 and "w" to 0.

#--- Stata ver. ---#
gen race_dum = 1 if race == "b"
replace race_dum = 0 if race == "w"

*** labeling of `race_dum`
label variable race_dum "1 if black, 0 if white"
#--- R ver. ---#
df <- df %>%
  mutate(race_dum = case_when(race == "b" ~ 1, race == "w" ~ 0))

## If there are some elements neither "b" nor "w", the element will be converted as "NA".
df %>% group_by(race_dum) %>% summarise(n = n())  ## check whether there are "NA"s
## # A tibble: 2 x 2
##   race_dum     n
##      <dbl> <int>
## 1        0  2435
## 2        1  2435

4.1. T-test for average

We test whether the mean value of variable call is equal to 0.5 or not. 

#--- Stata ver. ---#

** `call`: use the original variable
ttest call == 0.5 

** `race`: use the converted variable
ttest race_dum == 0.5 

#--- R ver. ---#

## `call`: use the original variable
t.test(
  df$call, 
  alternative = "two.sided",  ## select from "two.sided"(default), "less", "greater"
  mu = 0.5,  ## H0: equal to x, H1: not equal to x (default is 0)
  conf.level = 0.95  ## 95 % of confident level (default is 0.95)
)

## `race`: use the converted variable (abbrev.)
t.test(df$race_dum, mu = 0.5)
## 
##  One Sample t-test
## 
## data:  df$call
## t = -107.6, df = 4869, p-value < 2.2e-16
## alternative hypothesis: true mean is not equal to 0.5
## 95 percent confidence interval:

4.2. T-test for the difference of averages

We test whether the mean values of call are equal between race or not.
In this case, we can use both race (string) and race_dum (numeric).

There are two types of t-test according to the two variances are equal or not:

type two variances Stat’s option R’s option
t-test (normal) equal none (default) var.equal = TRUE
Welch’s t-test unequal unequal, w, unequal w var.equal = FALSE (default) 
#--- Stata ver. ---#
** t-test (normal)
ttest call, by(race)

** Welch's t-test
ttest call, by(race) w

#--- R ver. ---#
## t-test for education
t.test(call ~ race, data = df, var.equal = TRUE)

## t-test for education
t.test(call ~ race, data = df)
##

The equivalence

The table below compares the results of normal t-test and simple regression. We can see that both are same essentially.

coefficient st. dev. t-value significance
t-test -0.0320\(^{(1)}\) 0.0078 -4.1147 ***
regression -0.0320 0.0078 -4.1147 ***

\(^{(1)}\) mean value of the lower and upper 95% of significant intervals

The difference

Unlike t-test, regression can show \(R^2\) (0.0035) and \(adj. R^2\) (0.0033).
Although both values are small, it does not reject the significance of call back difference between races.
In other ward, the grade of \(R^2\) has nothing to do with causality analysis.

5. Single regression

We regress income (linc) on work experience (yearsexp).

5.1. Scatter plot

The largest value of yearsexp is 44 candidated by a black woman with category 4 of education.
However, her linc is unknown; thus, there is a space between 26 (the second largest) to 44 of the x-axis (yearsexp).

#--- Stata ver. ---#
** good
scatter linc yearsexp

** better to see
*** calculate `linc` according to `yearsexp`
bysort yearsexp: egen linc_yrexp = mean(linc)
*** plot
scatter linc_yrexp yearsexp

#--- R ver. ---#

## good
gg1 <- df %>%
  ggplot() +
  geom_point(aes(x = yearsexp, y = linc)) +
  theme_bw()

## better to see
gg2 <- df %>%
  ## summarize average of `linc` according to `yearsexp`
  group_by(yearsexp) %>%
  summarise_at("linc", mean, na.rm = TRUE) %>%  
  ## plot
  ggplot() +
  geom_point(aes(x = yearsexp, y = linc)) +
  theme_bw()

ggpubr::ggarrange(gg1, gg2)

5.2. Regression

We use lm() for linear regression in R, instead of reg in Stat.
If you haven’t install the package sandwich, run the following code install.packages("sandwich")

#--- Stata ver. ---#

** normal sd. error
regress linc yearsexp

** heteroskedasticity robust sd. error
regress linc yearsexp, robust

library(sandwich)

## normal sd. error
reg <- lm(linc ~ yearsexp, data = df)
stargazer(reg, type = "text")

## heteroskedasticity robust sd. error
robust_se <- vcovHC(reg, type = "HC1") %>%  ## heteroskedasticity robust variance-covariance matrix
  diag() %>% sqrt()  ## diag(): extract covariance,  sqrt(): covariance -> sd. error
stargazer(reg, type = "text",
          se = list(robust_se))

5.3. Prediction

#--- Stat ver ---#

** (1) prediction
predict yhat_1, xb 

** (2) plot
twoway(scatter linc_yrexp yearsexp)(line yhat_1 yearsexp)

#--- R ver. ---#

## (1) create a new dataframe which becomes x-axis.
df_new <- df %>% dplyr::select(yearsexp)

## (2) predict confidence interval at 95% significance level
conf_interval <- predict(reg, newdata = df_new, interval = "confidence", level = 0.95) %>% 
  as.data.frame()  ## convert matrix to dataframe
head(conf_interval)

## (3) conbine two dataframes: original dataframe and predicted confident interval
df1 <- data.frame()  ## reset `df1`
df1 <- cbind(df, conf_interval)

## (4) plot
ggplot() +
  geom_point(data = df1 %>% group_by(yearsexp) %>% summarise_at("linc", mean, na.rm = TRUE), 
    aes(x = yearsexp, y = linc)) +
  geom_line(data = df1, aes(x = yearsexp, y = fit), col = "orange") +  ## add line of fitted
  geom_line(data = df1, aes(x = yearsexp, y = lwr), col = "green") +  ## add curve of lower confident level
  geom_line(data = df1, aes(x = yearsexp, y = upr), col = "green") +  ## add curve of upper confident level
  theme_bw()
##        fit      lwr      upr
## 1 9.539085 9.522302 9.555869
## 2 9.539085 9.522302 9.555869
## 3 9.539085 9.522302 9.555869
## 4 9.539085 9.522302 9.555869
## 5 9.641166 9.594064 9.688268
## 6 9.539085 9.522302 9.555869


Shortcut for plotting

#--- Stata ver. ---#
twoway(scatter linc_yrexp yearsexp)(line yhat_1 yearsexp)(lfit linc yearsexp), /*
*/ legend(order(2 "predict" 3 "lfit"))

#--- R ver. ---#
ggplot() +
  geom_point(data = df %>% group_by(yearsexp) %>% summarise_at("linc", mean, na.rm = TRUE), 
             aes(x = yearsexp, y = linc)) +
  geom_smooth(data = df, aes(x = yearsexp, y = linc), method = "lm", level = 0.95) +
  theme_bw()
